a":{"about 1375–":"omkring 1375–Afdød","1400–1465":"1400–1465","1375–Male":"1375–Afdød","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1465":"1465","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","about 1375":"omkring 1375","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"about 1375–":"circa 1375–Overleden","1400–1465":"1400–1465","1375–Male":"1375–Overleden","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1465":"1465","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","about 1375":"circa 1375","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1375–":"about 1375–Deceased","1400–1465":"1400–1465","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1465":"1465","1375":"1375","1382":"1382","about 1375":"about 1375","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Frazier","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Fraser  .","Americanized form of French <b>Frégeau</b> (see   Fregeau  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Frachiseur","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Frazier  ."]},{"name":"Fregeau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Armand, Camille, Eloi, Fernand, Lucien, Michel, Normand.","French (<b>Frégeau</b>): metathesized form of <b>Fergeau</b>, from an old vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Ferreolus</i>, derived from <i>ferrum</i> ‘iron’. Compar   Frazier  ."]},{"name":"Fraser","meanings":["Scottish: apparently a nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>fraser(e)</i>, <i>fresere</i> ‘strawberry plant’. <i>Fresel</i> and <i>Frisel</i>, from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, are early variants of the Fraser surname, the modern Gaelicized form of which is <b>Friseal</b>. See   Frizzell  . The crest on the Scottish family's coat of arms takes the form of a strawberry plant, but its antiquity is unknown. Claims of a habitational derivation, in particular from a place called la Frézelière in Anjou (France), are attractive but they lack verifiable evidence.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","History: There are two clans Fraser in Scotland, with common ancestry going back to Simon Fraser of Keith in East Lothian, who lived in the 12th century. One of these clans has its seat at Philorth Castle (subsequently re-named Cairnbulg) on the northeast coast of Scotland. Sir Alexander Fraser, 8th laird of Philorth (<i>c.</i> 1536–1623) converted the fishing village of Faithlie into the burgh of Fraserburgh in the 1590s. The other clan is Fraser of Lovat, associated mainly with the city of Inverness are. They are descended from Simon Fraser, a younger son, who lived in the early 14th century. In Gaelic, the head of Clan Fraser of Lovat is known as <i>Mac Shimi</i> ‘son of Simon’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":80,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Frazier of Doncaster was born about 1375, in Doncaster, Yorkshire, England. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1375–":"umbes 1375–Surnud","1400–1465":"1400–1465